# 8-Bit Computer Architecture using Verilog HDL

## Project Overview

This project focuses on the design and implementation of a custom **8-Bit Computer Architecture** using **Verilog HDL**. The architecture is intended for FPGA implementation and consists of fundamental processor components such as registers, memory, ALU, control unit, instruction decoder, and input/output interfaces.

The objective is to understand computer organization at the hardware level by designing and integrating all CPU modules from scratch.

---

## Objectives

- Design an 8-bit computer architecture using Verilog HDL.
- Implement individual processor modules.
- Develop and verify RTL and Testbench code for each module.
- Integrate all modules into a complete processor system.
- Simulate and verify functionality before FPGA implementation.

---

## Instruction Set Architecture (ISA)

| Instruction | Opcode |
|------------|---------|
| LDA | 0000 |
| STA | 0001 |
| ADD | 0010 |
| SUB | 0011 |
| AND | 0100 |
| OR  | 0101 |
| NOT | 0110 |
| OUT | 0111 |

---

## Architecture Modules

The processor consists of the following modules:

1. Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU)
2. Accumulator (Register A)
3. Register B
4. Program Counter (PC)
5. Memory Address Register (MAR)
6. Instruction Register (IR)
7. Memory Unit
8. Control Unit
9. Instruction Decoder
10. Input Unit
11. Output Unit
12. Flag Register

---

## Architecture Block Diagram

The architecture follows a basic CPU datapath structure consisting of:

- Program Counter for instruction sequencing
- Memory for instruction and data storage
- Instruction Register for instruction holding
- Control Unit for control signal generation
- ALU for arithmetic and logical operations
- Registers for temporary data storage
- Input and Output interfaces for user interaction

